== Insider Tips for Success

#tip-box[
*Language is a Superpower:* While you can thrive professionally in English in Brussels, even basic conversational skills in French or Dutch will make a huge difference. It shows commitment and respect for the local culture, which is highly valued. Platforms like Duolingo are great for starting, but look into local language schools for faster progress.
]

#tip-box[
*Understand the "Three-Kiss" vs. Handshake Culture:* Social etiquette can be tricky. In professional settings, a firm handshake is the standard greeting. The three-cheek-kiss (`la bise`) is generally reserved for friends and informal acquaintances. When in doubt, offer a handshake.
]

#tip-box[
*Patience in Relationship Building:* Belgian professional culture can feel more reserved than in other countries. Don't be discouraged if networking feels slow at first. Focus on consistency and building genuine rapport. Follow up after meetings and look for ways to provide value to your new contacts.
]

#tip-box[
*Leverage Your Expat Status:* Being an expat is a strength. You bring an international perspective, adaptability, and often multilingual skills that are highly sought after, especially in an international hub like Brussels. Frame this as a key advantage in your CV, cover letter, and interviews.
]

